Consider the following subsets of Euclidean space \mathbb R^4
defined by

    U=\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{c}
    x \\
    y \\
    z \\
    w
    \end{array}\right] \middle|
            {{U_eq}}
    \right\}
        \hspace{1em} \text{and} \hspace{1em}
    W=\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{c}
    x \\
    y \\
    z \\
    w
    \end{array}\right] \middle|
            {{W_eq}}
    \right\}

Without writing a proof, explain why only one of these subsets is likely to be a subspace.

Consider the following subset of Euclidean space \mathbb R^3

    Q=\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{c}
    x \\
    y \\
    z
    \end{array}\right] \middle|
            {{Q_eq}}
    \right\}

Prove that Q is not a subspace.

Consider the following subset of Euclidean space \mathbb R^3

    R=\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{c}
    x \\
    y \\
    z
    \end{array}\right] \middle|
            {{R_eq}}
    \right\}

Prove that R is a subspace.
